Parliament did not ratify the amendment for Tymosenko's release
The Ukrainian parliament rejected, as part of an amendment to criminal law, the draft annulment of the paragraph on the indictment of Julia Tymosenko, the leader of the opposition.
MEPs rejected at second reading the proposed amendment to reduce penalties for economic offences, which could have opened the doors to freedom for the former Prime Minister currently imprisoned.
Tymosenko was sentenced in October to 7 years in prison for entering into an a priori disadvantageous agreement with Russia for the purchase of natural gas.
The judgment is not final and the court is due to rule on the sentenced woman's appeal in December.
Tymosenko calls the regime's political revenge judgment and has provoked a process of suspicions of court bias also in the west.
The proposed annulment of paragraph 365 of the Criminal Law, on the basis of which the former Prime Minister was convicted, was signed by 147 deputies.
It would have taken 226 votes to approve it.
