How Travel Prices Have Changed Since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time offered travel mainly to the countries of the socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays to East Germany, the Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and the Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in the Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A major exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia then the regime began to have a tilt towards the west and trips to Yugoslavia were very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that citizens of the socialist bloc (also Czechoslovaks) were not allowed to travel individually even within the framework of socialist countries.
In the event that the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually for example to Poland or the Soviet Union he needed a letter of invitation otherwise the individual travel was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the West, but you had to queue all night with a sleeping bag or have a "good knowledge" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The currency deal that was the condition for traveling to the west was denied to "politically incorrect" people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not exchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial means without the agreement of foreign exchange (Western currency) to travel to the west.
The Czechs most often spent their holidays in the country where there were consequently many country houses and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
Since 1989, Czech travel has undergone a major revolution.
Although until 1989 holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at their peak, last year Czechs spent 4 million days abroad in countries around the world.
The great paradox of which we are not aware today is that the most popular country is Croatia, where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because it was part of Yugoslavia at the time.
The abolition of visas in the 1990s in the western neighbouring countries caused a huge wave of short-term visits, especially to Austria, Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks could not travel for a long time by plane to the west that everyone wanted to see at least for a moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our income did not allow us to pay for the hotel or a pension.
The typical feature of a trip from Czech was at that time to take with you your own canned food, sausage, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech krona which allowed our tourists finally after decades of being able to freely buy Western currency.
Our standard of living as well as the average salary increased which caused around 1997 another important moment.
Thanks to a growing demand for travel travel agencies have started since 1997 to prepare tours with air charter routes that through contracts have tremendously reduced costs compared to what there was before.
In the late 1990s the Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world except the US which later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter to an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic was prepared.
Since this year as every year direct air charters take Czech tourists to the distant warm countries; this winter there will be 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
Over 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolutionary development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the US abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully rank in the group of developed countries.
In 2008 also the Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time yet in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad including ancillary charges. Crowns per person.
