The Pavilion that Moved
D'Ingeborg Wiensowski
A history of architecture with ups, downs and a Happy End: the Austrian pavilion for the world exhibitions in Brussels in 1958 won awards, was a museum in Vienna, remained empty and then fell into ruins.
Now it is open again and acts as an exhibition house.
If one is enthusiastic about modern post-war architecture, for its clear shapes, glass sheds, bright and bold looks and new building materials that are typical of the belief in technical progress, then the pavilion of the Austrian architect Karl Schwanzer for the world exhibition in Brussels in 1958 is a good and famous example.
The Schwanzer Pavilion was once awarded the "Grand Prix d'Architecture" for its lightweight, suspended steel and glass construction.
Construction is considered to this day as an important step in contemporary architecture.
He made the architects so famous, that he also built the Pavilion for the next Austrian World Exhibition.
With its legendary four-cylinder BMW house and its adjacent bowl-shaped construction in Munich, it finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion project as a temporary construction had been exhibited after the universal exhibition in the Swiss Garden at Vienna South Station, was transformed, and in 1962 a 20th century museum opened -
But the building was neither physically nor technically suitable for a museum - no walls to hang the works of art, so not a good environment.
However it was as long used, until contemporary art received a new edifice in Vienna.
Since 2001, the building has been empty and has become increasingly deteriorating.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has transformed the Pavilion, it now bears the name "Maison du 21<0xC3><0xA8>me si<0xC3><0xA8>cle" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
Tuesday evening the Belvéd<0xC3><0xA8>re museum opened, to which the house belongs, the first exhibition - a stroke of luck from any point of view.
The new start was carried out by Agn<0xC3><0xA8>s Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Belvedere Gallery in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, promoted an art historian to a considerable career among others in her youth as an artistic figure skater, later at Sotheby's, at the Guggenheim Museum and as the founding director of the Museum of Modern Art in Salzburg, she particularly carried out the transformation work with politicians and the protection of monuments.
Except for contemporary art, the works of sculptor Fritz Wotruba, whose foundation bears the same name, have been exhibited there, a café and a bookshop are located there, and an office must be built there.
Strict oversight, small budget
Krischanitz was therefore the ideal interpreter for the production.
Not only because he had sensitively transformed and expanded Joseph Olbracht’s secession and had won the competition, but because he had studied at the Technical University of Vienna and that for him the pavilion was “an extremely important place” where he had seen “virtually every weekend” exhibitions.
He knew the original project, and he knew the problems of the building, which lost in generosity and lightness as a result of his move to Vienna and its change of use.
In the current transformations, there were big problems: the building was "a chasm of energy," Krischanitz says.
The window profiles of the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ades were changed, fiberglass-reinforced insulating glass was laid and the roof replaced with a special safety glass.
Thermal bridge beams were reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled coatings were rehabilitated.
Two basements have made room for the new operation, a dimmed light panel between the house and the road provides lighting, a bridge leads to the entrance - it is almost a new construction, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
