Peter Englund's new book offers depth and generosity. Titled "The Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War", it begins with a long list of characters that holds your heart.
A tip to start with: carefully tear this page apart and make it your bookmark.
In this novel by Peter Englund, this list of characters will be your GPS, a beacon during those few moments when, as one of his men or women, you will be troubled and desperate in the mists of war.
Peter Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also the new permanent secretary of the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
He wrote here an unusual book which he accurately describes as "a work of anti-history."
It has some well-known names, important treatises or famous battles; there are almost no ambassadors or discussions on strategies and materials.
It's not so much a book about what happened, he explains, as a "book describing what it might look like." It includes "feelings, impressions, experiences and moods."
"Beauty and Grief" summarizes the wartime experiences of 20 more or less ordinary men and women, on both sides of the war, from young schoolgirls and botanists to climbers, doctors, paramedics and salesmen.
Some will become heroes.
Others will be prisoners of war, some will lose limbs, go mad, or lose their lives.
Their lives are shaking here like the candles of a church: while some are going out, new ones are being lit.
Peter Englund's book departs from traditional history books.
He denies the idea that World War I can only be summed up in the terrible trench war on the Western Front.
"Beauty and sorrow" skilfully describes other theatres of war: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia and East Africa.
The soldiers in this book are under hives; one spends Christmas in Egypt under the pyramids; tsetse flies are an intractable problem.
This book is moving from the first page.
War invades the lives of these people like a natural disaster, like a hurricane Katrina that stinks of cordite.
When gunshots sound in the distance, and you’re a housewife, do you stay or run away?
Who will come anyway?
Almost no one can understand what happened, or even the reasons for this war.
According to Peter Englund, “the lack of facts has been heightened by assumptions, hopes, fears, fixed ideas, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares, and rumors.”
"Beauty and Grief" follows such individuals as Florence Farmborough, an English nanny in the Russian army, as well as Richard Stumpf, a young sailor from the German high seas fleet.
Their stories are mainly drawn from memoirs, letters and other documents already published.
The versions of their lives can be terrifying or exciting, but are most preserved thanks to the accumulation of small moments and isolated details.
Most are dealing with deprivation and the ability to get out of it.
In telling the story of a German schoolgirl, Peter Englund writes: "Ersatz, everywhere ersatz."
