While Breivik acted alone, he was far from being on cyberspace: he had spent much of the time before the attack on his computer, chatting with a few of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers want to know more about these people.
But how to find them?
Easy... Log in to Facebook.
“We realized it wasn’t that hard to find them,” says Jamie Bartlett, lead author of a recent report by DEMOS’ think tank on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook is so full of personal information, says Jamie Bartlett, that researchers could simply use the site’s advertising tool to find the people they’re looking for with scientific accuracy — the way marketers have been doing it for years.
Jamie Bartlett's team discovered that half a million members are fans of far-right groups in Europe. She targeted them with ads, but instead of linking them to a new group or product, the ads invited users to respond to a survey. The questions asked were about their own level of education, attitudes to violence and optimism about their future.
By getting in touch with these people through Facebook, Jamie Bartlett and his colleagues were able to interview 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries - without leaving the office.
“It’s a new way of doing research,” says Jamie Bartlett.
Some results are not at all surprising: the online supporters of right-wing groups are rather men, young and against immigration.
But surprisingly, “those who associate online and offline activism are more reasonable, more democratic and less violent than those who remain behind their computer screen.”
The DEMOS study is just one example of how Facebook has become the new must-have tool in the hands of scientists.
Think tanks, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study all topics that affect health issues such as social trends, through "Likes", publications on walls and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, the “data supernova” generates a search explosion, increasing the number of search jobs whose site name appears in the title by almost 800% compared to the last five years.
For some researchers, the advantage of Facebook lies in the fact that it allows you to study people you couldn’t approach on the street.
“Before, when you were trying to conduct investigations into people from the British National Party, it was very difficult to identify them.”
“You were supposed to go to the party, but they would never have allowed you to come in,” says Jamie Bartlett.
"Facebook avoids all this - you have direct access to their information."
Others say the site could offer a way to identify and address health and social issues.
According to a recent study by D. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin-Madison, and his colleagues, young students who talked on Facebook about their drunken exploits were vastly more likely to be alcoholic than discrete students about it.
Megan Moreno suggests that fellow students, such as counselors, could monitor the site and intervene to eventually help a student whose status would talk too often about alcohol.
“You can’t treat a problem if you don’t diagnose it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author of Megan Moreno and director of the Center for Children’s Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle.
“We know how to identify children who are at risk, and who would otherwise not be recognized.”
Facebook also constantly accesses the information of its users.
The site's data team studied statistics regarding the love situation and Valentine's Day, turnout in the 2010 midterm elections and a national happiness index (thanks to information only available - digital freedom champions have long argued that the site could make its treasure trove of data available to other people for research purposes).
But Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they like it or not – in exchange for being able to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site is allowed to access your information.
But what happens when Facebook users are part of a survey they haven’t even heard of?
While researchers have well-defined guidelines on how to collect information other than through the Internet, there is something else online.
“I don’t think a lot of users have ever thought about whether a researcher could study their profile,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, according to a 2006 study he conducted by observing the Facebook walls of his students.
"As far as they know, the exchanges were only seen by their friends."
Then comes the question of methodology.
Even without going through the Internet, there is no guarantee that the subject of a study is completely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know the degree of truth of a profile or on a user’s wall.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do in reality are two totally different things,” Selwyn said.
That's why, despite his experience as a technology researcher, Neil Selwyn believes that a notebook and a pen are still the best tools one can use.
“Nothing can replace the real world and contact with people,” he says.
"Social studies are supposed to address the social aspect - and social is not in front of a computer."
