2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of the Government of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdez, self-called change, which has generated great expectations regarding the advances of the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, the increase is not observed, in exchange there is a deterioration of the main indicators.
The low temperatures of February, apart from causing trillions of losses for the agricultural sector, have limited the opportunities of the state economy for growth, caused a contraction of economic activity in general by 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic decrease of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which has affected the dynamism of other economic sectors.
According to the report of frost assignments issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, there was damage of 582 million 835 hectares cultivated, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent suffered partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and peas.
The decline in economic activity has generated, until November, a constant increase in the first thousand people unemployment rate in the State, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography 9 percent the unemployment rate of the State during the first three quarters of the year there was an accelerated increase, because while from January to March 55 thousand 053 Sinaloa were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent for the Population 5 percent, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, according to the economist Gerardo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly depending on the actions carried out by public policy.
“What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that is due to various factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by legislation approved in Congress to combat money laundering, because for people who earn dollars in an illicit way it is not easy for them to work to earn them, to invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Detained migration
L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Cervantes pointed out that the rise in unemployment is also due to a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the state to go to work abroad in the United States has been limited, firstly because of the difficulties of entry and secondly because when they enter they already have a lot of difficulty in finding work, these people stay here and ask for sources of work, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Lack of seriousness
The analysis of the sinaloen labour market worsens considering the high level of lack of seriousness that prevails among working conditions, according to INEGI, 60.38 percent of the population employed in this state works there without contributing as a worker to any social insurance institution.
Apart from unemployment and lack of seriousness, another reason for the state's lag is low wages, the entity has the lowest salaries in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Insurance and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Security.
The average monthly income of Sinaloa workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, much lower than the national average, which stands at 7,375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
Apart from the decline in economic activity and rising unemployment, in 2011 there was the largest reduction in Foreign Direct Investment in the last 10 years, according to the Secretariat of Economy of January to June the FDI of the State reached 630 thousand 697, representing a decrease of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143 thousand 312 recorded in the same period.
In turn, the Secretariat for Economic Development of the State Government has a total investment of 17.280 trillion pesos per year, recorded mainly by companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the State Government requested in July at the public congress the approval of a loan of 3 trillion pesos, intended for investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the aim of reactivating the economy, the approval of the State Congress was 2,600 trillion pesos and until November no profit was observed.
