For the representatives of the employers’ sector, the first year of Mario L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Valdés’ government demonstrates a lack of government management capacity.
Miguel Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that in 2011 there was no harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the State Government.
"The performance of the economy of Sinaloa during this year was really very poor, we have to work intensely to recover the ground that we lost this year, in 2012 we have to double our efforts, it was necessary to align the effort of all and above all the already synchronized good progress of this new government team, hopefully next year will be much better," he said.
Slow economic growth
Loredo L<0xC3><0xB3>pez said events like the frosts at the beginning of the year have held the state’s economy back and curtailed its yield and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, among which the frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not rotate fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows us to have an acceptable level of flow in the processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we close well below the expectations that we had," he says.
Redefining the Vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Confederation of Employers of the Mexican Republic of Sinaloa said that we want to channel the state towards productive activities of more dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that we have worked, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program that redefines the vocation and economic direction of the State, because it is important that we detonate the full potential of the material and human resources of Sinaloa," he says.
