The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put the country on the brink of economic disaster
The Prime Minister-designate, Mario Monti, will meet Wednesday with the President of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and has endangered the entire Eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed Sunday, would meet Wednesday with the president, Giorgio Napolitano, to confirm that he can form the government.
It is expected that he will present a cabinet composed in its majority by technocrats, although it is not clear when the new executive will assume his position.
Monti said he would present the president with the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," the former EU commissioner told reporters.
Monti did not say explicitly that he could form a government, but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
"The framework is now well laid out," he added.
Monti completed the process to form a government in less than three days, in a shorter time than normal, as Italy grapples with a political and financial crisis that has pushed the costs of its debt to levels impossible to sustain.
The new administration led by former EU commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain the confidence in Italy that had been affected.
Stressing the pressure on Monti to hurry, the instability of the markets placed the yield of Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland had to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, leader of Italian employers’ Confindustria, told the media after her meeting with Monti: “We said we would strongly support this government.”
We believe that this Government is the last opportunity for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were greatly boosted by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign last Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts will have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the center-right party, told reporters.
The support of PDL, the largest Italian party, is significant because until now many of its members had opposed the technocratic majority government that Monti forms.
Parliamentary support
Monti's new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in its efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by noting that a bankruptcy of Monti would be a disaster.
On Monday, Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions, employers’ groups and youth and women’s organizations.
He will finish his reunion tour on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed Sunday by Napolitano, who enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it was clear that Berlusconi would resign, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over the new prime minister’s success.
Saving Italy, with a public debt of 1.9 trillion euros, would be too much for the Eurozone’s current financial defenses.
Monti said his government should persist until the upcoming elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before moving the elections forward.
Monti said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist that it should be trained only by specialists, an indication of their objections to a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources have reported that reciprocal mistrust and disagreements between parties complicate the attempt to include political figures.
