It makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also becomes more interesting for people.
With this tour, you will celebrate 20 years of trajectory.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything you’ve accomplished?
Yes, absolutely.
In the first place, I think none of us ever imagined we were going to form a big rock band, and the fact that we’ve been doing it for over 20 years makes it sound like a dream.
We continue to recount our blessings and being able to continue making music together is very exciting.
We love each other and we love creating music.
We’re lucky to go to places in the world we’ve always wanted to go.
Things couldn't get any better for us.
What does it mean for you to have been a fundamental element in the creation of grunge?
It has always been an honor for us to be part of this group of large groups.
We are very friendly with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and is uncommon.
From time to time, a group emerges from a city, but it is much stranger when five or ten groups leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and it is an honor for us to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year we went to a festival with Alice in Chains and we went to Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to still be friends with all of them and it’s an honor for us to be part of that Seattle sound that came out.
It’s also very strange that a group like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, and only this is much longer than many groups normally last.
First, I believe we are all lucky to still be alive, and second, we all care about others.
We are all close friends and thanks to this there are musical boulevards that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We have confidence in each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t get any better.
Your relationship with the word celebrity hasn’t been easy; however, thanks to your success, you’ve been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we grew up, it was easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure we don’t spend too much time touring because it’s easy to get into this game from the big crowds and people who love your music.
If we don’t forget that people are there for the music, it helps us to remember that we have to respect the music and what it brought, without thinking about the fact that we are famous and a rock star, which is not really of interest to any of us.
How do you remember your other project, Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for almost three years and we didn’t release a record until Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration for the fact that it lasted so little and the most important thing is the fact that we are still very close friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who started in the band with us and when I listen to a song or I see a picture I think of the amazing person Andy was and how he made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to talk, to work.
He was a surprising human being and we miss him.
The national band Las Robertas will open the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder and for that you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with different proposals and this was the band we liked the most, so we are looking forward to seeing what Las Robertas can offer live and it has to be very entertaining.
Why do you always change the lyrics of Yello Ledbetter live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don’t know.
He is the one who sings it and I believe he does it with the first words he imagines.
As a bassist, what are his influences?
There are so many...
Among the first I remember are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many influences, that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep grunge high despite the fact that it is no longer fashionable?
I think we all feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I just mentioned, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the bands that came up at the same time and, if that matters now, I think it’s wonderful because it’s a music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making the best music ever.
At first, his music had a more obscure content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It’s interesting, because I think there are songs on the new album that seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very obscure songs, even though these may sound a bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed played them for me, I cried when I listened to them and these are deeply obscure songs.
I think if you grow up and there’s a trauma in your life and you lose to a parent or friend, these things start to influence your art and your music and these songs, no doubt, represent that to me.
I also think we can be happy and even so we can make dark music.
