Secretary Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come gives details of the plane crash in which the Secretary of the Government, Francisco Blake and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretariat of Communications and Transport (SCT) reported that the results of the accident in which the Secretary of Government, Francisco Blake Mora and seven others lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter struck directly against the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot being able to try a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come, Secretary of Communications and Transport, mentioned that before the aircraft took off, the pilot found that the weather conditions were adequate to fly.
"Elements that seem to indicate that the unit had various contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with the trees at 25 meters where the unit lost the fuselage."
He also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it met the requirements for transporting personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations made in the impact area do not report the appearance of parts on the ground.
"In a search it was reported that there are no parts or components of the aircraft in another location, the impact was presented in a structural way.
“The helicopter was designed for 19 passengers and met the requirements to carry them.
The ground had a slope of seven to 30 degrees of inclination.
For the time being, the secretary has assured that a priority is to have the results as soon as possible; but the investigation can last a few months, it can even last a year.
In turn, Gilberto L<0xC3><0xB3>pez Meyer, General Manager of Airports and Auxiliary Services, assured that at the time of the impact, the Presidential Staff helicopter was operating at cruise speed and it happened on a soft ascending ground.
"This information supports the hypothesis of normal cruiser operation at the time of impact," he says.
During the press conference, TBS incumbent Pérez J<0xC3><0xA1>come listed six important elements in the investigation:
Visual flight:
According to aeronautical regulations, the flight was performed according to the rules of visual flight, which implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Weather conditions:
Reports in the IACM mentioned adequate conditions for take-off, and as the aircraft advanced towards the border area between DF and the State of Mexico there were low-level cloud layers.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to cloudy conditions the crew searched for a lower height area and more visibility towards the Cuernavaca Valley.
Location of impact.
The coordinates of the impact and the last recording of the aircraft on the radar coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration of the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a reduced area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact took place on a straight and lateral trajectory.
The dispersion model of the aircraft debris makes it possible to assume that the helicopter collided with the ground under conditions of structural integrity.
No traces of fire or explosion were detected:
At the site of the accident, there is still no trace of any type of explosion or fire in the remains of the aircraft.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that the aircraft had had multiple contacts with the ground.
During fieldwork, parts of the aircraft were found at a height of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the ground had a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which he possibly disarticulated along his journey.
The information provides evidence that appears to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts with the ground.
After careful research in an area wider than the encircled area, around the accident, no scattered parts of the aircraft were found, which supports the presumption that the impact took place under conditions of structural integrity.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find the Obesity Gene
Social Insurance leads an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people; this is supported by IPN specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) has announced that it is leading an investigation to discover the obesity gene in the case of children and young people, called the ‘Children’s and Adolescents’ Obesity Genetics Protocol’ which will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Specialties Hospital of the National Medical Center of the 20th Century, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The investigation invites the participation of the population with or without the right, to present themselves to the participating sports units of the IMSS in Valle de México, where the evidence to minors is carried out every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Estado de México Poniente) and that from October 8, the activity takes place in the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Unit (Estado de México Oriente).
After reaching the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors, the study will continue in the Independencia Sports Unit (south of Distrito Federal) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of Distrito Federal).
He explained that the objective of this investigation is to know the components and importance of genetics in relation to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors for preventing the onset of chronic degenerative diseases in Mexican children and youth.
As World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years, with the consent and under the supervision of their parents, for the application of the specific questionnaires related to food.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and family history of their diseases, to avoid the risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics will be applied to all participants (searches to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez pointed out that this investigation is the result of the concern of health professionals for the alarming weight gain in the case of minors.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there was a 77 percent increase in obesity among boys and 47 percent for girls, and a dramatic increase in overweight," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the rationale for the search for markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, Mexicans have 65 percent Indo-American inheritance, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn excess energy consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the integral evaluation of the children, which allows to detect if they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored pleats (acanthosis) on the neck and forearm indicate the likelihood of suffering from metabolic alterations and even pre-diabetes.
The information is managed in a confidential manner, and doctors hand it over in writing to the parents, who explain each of the measures and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting in front of the TV for most of the day and using means of transportation instead of walking for short distances.
Another cause is high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales - meatballs with cornmeal wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, hamburgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid blackcurrants
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better yield, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement were resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair about 200,000 blackcurrants each rainy season in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, warns Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at UNAM’s Faculty of Chemistry (FQ), who has assured that if the process of building and maintaining the same bituminous pavement is adequate, the same blackcurrants could be reduced or reduced.
During his lecture A Technological Opinion on Blackcurrants, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory he is responsible for is developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve yield, and consequently, the formation of blackcurrants.
He explained that asphalt, the heavier part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of almost 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of asphalt is not uniform and changes during the day depending on environmental and temperature conditions, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the streets of Ciudad de México in their majority were covered by a flexible pavement, composed of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that form the layer, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles pass through it generating forces, it allows the forces to propagate very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would propagate better, the chemical engineer thought.
On the asphalt layer, he said, a last layer called a rolling layer is put, made of fine stone, that is, sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide grip on the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes the forces, the rolling layer also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material from which it is made must be treated.
Climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, as these significantly affect the yield of the asphalt layer.
When the soil gets wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to come out, which softens all the layers of the pavement and therefore causes blackcurrants.
In the process of forming a blackcurrant, he says, the first one that breaks is the rolling film and only later is affected the asphalt layer, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be taken care of at the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of blackcurrant and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and guarantee its satisfaction, to avoid the frequent formation of blackcurrant.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to investigate and work on asphalt, for example, bituminous emulsions, which in other countries already exist on the market and make it possible to repair blackcurrant easily and without having to use high temperatures.
