Thus was the work of the person of Cali who identified the body of Alfonso Cano
A typist from Cali has gone down in history as the man who confirmed the death of "Alfonso Cano".
The work of these officials is crucial.
On November 4, a typist from the CTI of Cali went down in history as the person who confirmed the identity of the supreme leader of the FARC: "Alfonso Cano", confronting his fingerprints.
Of the seven typists who work in the local offices of the CTI, this week it was the turn of "availability" of Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, a man from Puerto Tejada who has been working for 21 years in the field of judicial investigation.
At the beginning of his career, Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez worked in the municipalities of Choc<0xC3><0xB3>, where many times he had to spend more than five days in the forest to get to the place where the corpses were to be identified.
In the year 2000 he was transferred to the capital of Valle and after taking adequate courses, he specialized in dactyloscopy, which is the study of the skin of friction, i.e. the palms and feet.
During the week of the operation against Alfonso Cano, Eliazar was warned to take clothes with him for at least three days.
Something very big was waiting for him.
On Friday night he left for Cauca in a helicopter from Palmira.
He knew that he had to identify two corpses and that one of them was suspected to be that of the man who ran the oldest guerrilla in the world, so he was asked to take the card with the ten fingerprints of Guillermo Le<0xC3><0xB3>n S<0xC3><0xA1>enz (his real name).
But when he arrived with the investigative team at the place of the corpse, he did not recognize it by its physical appearance, because it was very different from the one he had seen in the media.
He had no beard, he was dressed like a local farmer, without glasses and much leaner.
But fingerprints don't lie.
Accompanied by a Galtonian magnifying glass, ink, a sampler and a lantern, Eliazar compared the body’s fingerprints with those on the map.
His eye did not deceive him: it was "Alfonso Cano".
That same night, the man from Puerto Tejada was the official who confirmed to Defense Minister Juan Carlos Pinz<0xC3><0xB3>n that yes, he was the supreme leader of the FARC.
In Search of the Footprint
For a typist from Sij<0xC3><0xAD>n de Cali the recognition that President Juan Manuel Santos made to Eliazar Gonz<0xC3><0xA1>lez, in a press conference for the operation against "Cano", is very significant.
A lot of people don't know our work.
Dactyloscopy is an exact science, with no margin for error, that can be crucial in solving crimes.
Aside from identifying the bodies, typists support investigations for crimes such as theft and homicide and confirm the identity of those captured.
When captured, many offenders present false identity cards or do not have any documents.
We take their fingerprints and search the database.
The researcher said that in a case of theft he had to remove a part of the wall of a house, because in that place the thief had pressed his hand to get out a safe full of jewelry and money.
“The walls are difficult because they are not adequate surfaces to take a fingerprint from, but in this case we were able to get the fingerprint from the whole hand and identify the offender who had participated in different robberies,” he recalls.
Footprints can also rule out or confirm suspects in homicide cases.
Recently we found a dead man, with bottles of drink around him.
Through the investigation, it was determined that a parent may be a suspect in the crime and indeed a fingerprint on the bottle coincided.
Even if it doesn't guarantee that he's the killer, it puts him on the crime scene.
A CTI typist explained that "fingerprints of objects are extracted with chemical or physical reagents."
When they appear, a sampler or strip is used to collect them.
Subsequently, the fingerprints are sent to Asif, the database of declines, or to the National Civil Registry.
“The problem is that there are still a lot of undocumented Colombians,” the CTI expert said.
He explained that not everything is as shown in the CSI television program.
Since everything that shines is not gold, everything that one touches does not necessarily become an imprint.
However, it can be used if the necessary confrontation is carried out.
