GDP rises by 1.5% thanks to domestic consumption and ends the downward spiral at the beginning of March
Since March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, recuperating even after the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst disaster in the country since World War II.
Initial estimates by the Government of Tokyo have estimated material losses at $300,000 million, a blow that, despite the challenging global environment, appears to have abated.
After three consecutive quarters of falls, the data on Gross Domestic Product between July and September served to turn the page definitively: GDP rose 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and 6% in annualized rates.
The second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year starts in March 2012 - also represents the largest rate of increase since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly due to the resumption of acquisitions of equipment to restore the areas devastated by the earthquake and the subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared to the 0.9% drop in capital expenditures observed from January to March, the first decline after six months of uninterrupted growth.
However, the real stimulus of the Japanese economy is not based exclusively on the Keynesian impulse that invites to take advantage of the crisis to consolidate - or rebuild - infrastructure, use the shortcomings to grow from zero.
Japan has woken up mainly thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This increased by 1%, driven by higher spending on vehicles, travel and entertainment.
