Energy policy:
The facts must prevail over the dogmas.
If there is one subject that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or under the influence of emotion, it is energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence purchasing power and the competitiveness of enterprises.
It is healthy that an election meeting is an opportunity to reflect on such issues and the place nuclear energy holds.
The debate will only be fruitful if it explores the full range of economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
While there are 7 billion human beings on the planet, demographic change will result in a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, unless it deprives a huge portion of the world’s population of a vital element.
At the same time, it will be necessary to overcome the scarcity of fossil resources to continue to produce electricity permanently, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to combat climate change, a topic that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not change any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains isolated in its decision to give up nuclear power.
This is neither the case of Belgium, which submits its own to the need to be able to find a replacement source capable of replacing itself, nor of Switzerland, which just intends to build only the latest generation of power plants.
Conversely, Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India, Brazil, to name but a few, are pursuing their plans with determination.
The United States decided after Fukushima to add a unit to their park by resuming construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, focused on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, the reality contradicts the discourse.
The choice of Berlin will result in higher electricity prices, an energy dependence exacerbated by the increased use of imported gas, especially from Russia, a jump in CO2 emissions caused by the construction of gas and coal plants.
Within a few months, all these unpleasant effects are already being felt.
The case of Denmark is to be meditated on.
European champion of wind, from which it derives 30% of its electricity, it is also one of the largest users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; under which, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
Conversely, thanks to the consistency of our energy policy, our neighbours pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor of competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of the industrial tool on the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
As a result, any significant reduction in the share of nuclear power would lead to a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would make illusory the beautiful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of purchasing power.
A price that a large majority of French people refuse to pay, especially since they do not show opposition in principle to this energy, the polls show.
Let us remember that our country’s energy policy has built an industrial sector of 125,000 direct jobs and 410,000 induced jobs.
Strongly exporting, it leads to a galaxy of SMEs specializing in international markets and makes them very creative of non-relocatable jobs.
If France were to decide to exit nuclear, it would sacrifice many of these SMEs by reducing as a skin of grief the 6 billion euros per year of French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
Which electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years when the decline of its manufacturer would be programmed?
In order to solve the energy equation, it must be admitted that there is no source of miraculous electricity production, nor is there any diabolical one.
Areva's development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementarity of energy sources.
For nuclear power, maintaining the highest level of safety is an absolute imperative.
In France, we have a safety authority that exercises uncompromising and transparent control over existing power plants and the Flamanville construction site.
Our teams, whose professionalism is recognized, are inhabited by the same obsession with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious accidents.
Only one, Three Mile Island, intervened under normal operating conditions; it remained without human or environmental consequences.
In Chernobyl, the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults caused the drama.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was the result of two natural disasters of unprecedented scale that caused the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
As a result of this approach and cooperation between the French and German safety authorities, operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design that makes it able to withstand such phenomena.
While it is considered by all electricians eager to build a power plant, stopping its construction in Flamanville would be a magnificent gift offered to the competitors of Areva and EDF by leaving them free to take the lead in the unavoidable development of nuclear.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy mix for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan manoeuvres dominate such a decisive debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy conducted under Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various angles - congestion of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the politics of the figure, compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has made the news, the Minister of the Interior (read Liberation of May 23) proclaiming in passing that France "does not need foreign talents, masons and restaurant waiters".
But it is rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the left and the right.
On the right, the tone was given by Jacques Chirac who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem in a country comprising nearly 2 million immigrant workers", and on the left, by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot accommodate all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
In 2005, fear of the invasion of the national territory by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared on both the left and right.
For both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden to the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that will be deigned to be accorded to immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confines himself to banalities, indicating that co-development will solve our "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may pay electorally; but it is economically very costly.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron recall in a recent book synthesizing the latest knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is broad consensus among scholars on the positive impact of migration flows on economic growth.
Restricting immigration anemia growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of migrants are based on the idea that they may replace national workers, especially the low-skilled, who are putting downward pressure on their wages.
But experience shows that, in reality, immigrants are much more complementary than substitutes for national employees, mainly working in sectors where there is a shortage of jobs.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national employees, and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not follow the supply of jobs.
A positive effect on wages
In the same way that a surgeon will have difficulty working in a country with a shortage of anaesthetists, these complementarities between nationals and migrants mean that the arrivals of immigrants have a positive effect on the salaries and employment of nationals.
Giovanni Peri calculated that a 1% increase in migratory flows leads to an increase between 0.6 and 0.9% of real wages in the long term.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity brought by immigrants contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (high proportion of naturalized immigrants among the American Nobel Prize winners; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants are also net contributors to social systems, averaging 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant arriving at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (revenue minus expenditure) of €150,000 to public budgets on average over his or her lifetime.
Nicolas Sarkozy wanted, at the beginning of his term, to look for the missing growth points "with the teeth".
The teeth in question, used to deter immigrants, had the exact opposite effect.
