Democracy is a precious good; it is also a fragile good.
The European continent should be able to remember him who, for having invented it in Athens more than two thousand years ago, experienced throughout the twentieth century the tragedies of the Great War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that it would suffice, for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, to exercise the vote, and to exercise it in the most direct way possible.
We know, since Napoleon the Little, that this was an ease of thought.
Universal suffrage, in order to be the necessary condition of democracy, is not the sufficient condition and can even become an "instrument of oppression", as the republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot once said.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public mind, values, organization, separation and control of powers, education, enlightenment, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis of the Europe we are experiencing is an economic crisis, but it is also and first of all a crisis of politics and democracy.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum will have been a double revealer in this respect: that of the need for a powerful return of politics, but also that of the disturbing feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be thought of in order to be overcome.
The truth is that the front lines of democratic struggle have now shifted, and for many of them, Republican soldiers are no longer firing in the right direction.
We have nothing to gain from demanding a succession of national referendums, organized according to necessity and in dispersed order.
A whistle-blower to the absolute European monarch or a leap into the emptiness of the nationalist retreat: what a choice for the citizen!
No, we do not want cuts, but a common, full-fledged, serene and continuous exercise of choice and democracy, this time at European level.
There are no crises in Greece, in Italy, in Spain, in Portugal - we can no longer stop the enumeration - because there is only one crisis, and it is in Europe.
It is Europe as a whole that is bowing to the dictates of markets and rating agencies, suffering from its impotence and lack of solidarity.
The whole of Europe is being humiliated on the international stage.
There are concerns about transfers of sovereignty to Europe - but it is the whole of Europe that is slowly losing its sovereignty, and with it each of its nations.
The urgency is to give back to popular sovereignty the leadership of the European project.
Because together, Europeans will be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from markets and prepare for the future by investing.
The way out of the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, except of course to lead us to disaster.
After having long opposed this proposal by the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Oh, yeah.
But to think of it without a stronger political and democratic integration, and lived as such by the citizens, would be a new madness and a new impasse.
We must take on a new stage in the construction of Europe.
To make the Republic in France, it was necessary to "make" Republicans.
The Revolution in the interests could not suffice.
This lesson remains valid.
We need to build a more economically integrated Europe.
This can only be achieved by building a more politically democratic Europe, a genuine European people's sovereignty.
To make Europe, let us make Europeans.
"Contactless" smart cards are becoming more widespread
The world's smart card fair opens Tuesday in Villepinte, near Paris, in an optimistic climate.
The year 2011 is expected to end on an 11% increase in global sales of microprocessor cards (bank card, phone with SIM card...), to more than 6 billion units, according to the firm Eurosmart.
The most powerful segment is contactless technology, which allows you to pay for public transport or pay for your purchases by simply approaching a reader's card.
This year, 460 million contactless smart cards are expected to be sold worldwide, up from 320 million a year earlier!
Their share is expected to increase further in 2012 (580 million units expected) and represent nearly 10% of the global smart card market (6.925 million cards).
Europe has long lagged behind the Asia-Pacific region and is gaining ground for contactless payment.
Some 26 million Visa credit cards are already equipped with this feature and 75,000 payment terminals accept it.
In France, the beginnings are more modest: 400,000 Visa contactless cards have been deployed.
But the large surfaces make the bites double.
This year, Carrefour issued 2.5 million contactless MasterCard Pass cards.
To take the next step, banks now need to equip their customers.
"Two major French institutions have committed to systematically distribute to their customers in the future bank cards equipped for contactless," said Gérard Nébouy, General Manager of Visa Europe France.
Banks are testing mobile payment
But this is only a first step towards the payment method of the future: the mobile phone.
Few devices today are equipped with NFC (Near Field Communication) technology essential for carrying out transactions.
“They were late.”
“But they should finally see a real boom next year.”
“We expect to sell 80 to 120 million units worldwide in 2012,” said Marc Bertin, President of Eurosmart.
But the banks are taking the lead.
Crédit Agricole announced yesterday the launch of a test from December to June in Caen.
The iPhones of some 200 customers and employees will be equipped with a case that allows contactless payment.
The BPCE has a similar project in Strasbourg and Marseille.
And the Société Générale, too, said yesterday it was preparing to put an offer on the market allowing its customers to pay without contact with their mobile.
From the Sahara to Nigeria, the terrorist front is expanding
Paris is concerned about the links between al-Qaida in the Islamic Maghreb and the Boko Haram sect.
Suspected for a long time, ties between the al-Qaida terrorist group in the Islamic Maghreb (Aqmi) and the Nigerian sect Boko Haram are confirmed.
On Sunday, Algeria's deputy foreign minister, Abdelkader Messahel, even said that Algiers has now "acquired certainty".
“The way the two organizations operate and the intelligence reports show that there is good cooperation,” he said.
Paris seems to be doing a similar analysis.
The investigation into the kidnapping of two Frenchmen in Niger last January would have uncovered bridges.
Kidnapped in a restaurant in Niamey by relatives of Aqmi, Antoine de Léocour and Vincent Delory were to be killed the next day along with several of their captors in an operation launched by French special forces.
In the rubble of the intervention, French and Nigerien investigators had to find several telephone chips belonging to the terrorists.
Terrorist Axis
The analysis of the calls made points to several interlocutors based in Mali, Niger and Nigeria.
According to Radio France Internationale (RFI), two issues are of particular interest to investigators: one leads to a Nigerian who has stayed for a long time in Maiduguri, a city in northern Nigeria, the cradle of Boko Haram and the other to a man who claims to be close to Aqmi and the sect.
"This is a step forward, but we must probably wait for more formal evidence before talking about operational cooperation between Aqmi and Boko Haram."
"But it's possible."
"It has been known for years that the sect is receiving financial and intellectual support from outside and is increasingly active," says Kunle Amuwo, a Nigerian researcher.
In recent months these "supports" had been increasingly evident in the evolution and speeches of Boko Haram or in its operating methods, which now involve the use of suicide bombs or explosive devices increasingly complex and of the same invoice as those used by Aqmi.
The international community, starting with Washington, has therefore pressured Abuja to take into account the problems posed by Boko Haram.
The Nigerian authorities have long regarded the group as an enlightened community of little interest.
A quick success
Founded in 2002 in Maiduguri around a mosque, a school and the fundamentalist imam Mohammed Yusuf, Boko Haram - which means in Hausa "Western education is a sin" - advocates the establishment of an Islamic emirate in the Muslim north of Nigeria.
In this poor region, the association is enjoying rapid success.
It politicizes itself and demands strict respect for sharia law while its militants engage in the fight against the impious central government.
The latter are primarily aimed at churches, bars, administrations.
In 2009, Boko Haram activists were particularly active, multiplying attacks on police stations.
Abuja's reaction is, as usual, nuanceless.
The army invades the city, there are 800 dead.
Mohammed Yusuf, arrested alive, is killed in prison.
From then on, the sect would radicalize and leave its northern fiefdoms.
Last Christmas, she claimed an attack that killed 80 people in Jos, then another in Abuja.
In June, it was again in Abuja that Boko Haram attacked the secure police headquarters during a suicide attack, its first.
In August, the local headquarters of the United Nations will be its first international target.
The creation of a terrorist axis in Africa that would sail from Mauritania to Somalia through Nigeria now worries all security specialists.
While Aqmi has invested Mali and Niger, and al-Shebab Somalis are operating in Kenya, Boko Haram appears as a new threat in the heart of the continent.
Last week, during an interview in Nigeria with President Goodluck Jonathan, Alain Juppé warned against Boko Haram and said he was ready "to share all the information".
The world according to Republican presidential candidates
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, and Rick Perry compete for simplicity and ignorance.
Can a crisis-weakened America manage a complex world with simple, even simplistic, ideas?
Listening to Republican presidential candidates, voters might believe it.
In recent days, Mitt Romney, Herman Cain, Rick Perry and others have been multiplying thunderous statements and shortcuts in foreign policy, traditionally a Republican strong point.
On China, on Iran, on aid to Israel, the slogans - often unsubstantiated - are fusing.
Mitt Romney, best placed in the race for the nomination of the "Grand Old Party", threatened to drag the Chinese before the WTO and question them "for manipulation of their currency", a theme that has carried in an America exasperated by the migration of entire sections of its industry to Asia.
Worse if it means starting a trade war, he said.
Jon Huntsman, Obama’s former ambassador to China and the only candidate to have a sophisticated foreign policy vision, nearly strangled himself in the face of an attitude that “flatters” emotions.
He called for a muscular but constructive dialogue with Beijing (Obama’s current position).
But Huntsman, who stagnates in the depths of the polls, remains inaudible.
In the image of Reagan
Romney also promised military strikes on Iran if sanctions fail to stop its nuclear program.
“If I am elected, I will arrest Iran,” he said.
“If Obama is re-elected, they will have the bomb.”
He also vowed to increase military aid to Israel, accusing Obama of failing to meet his obligations to that partner.
Entrepreneur Herman Cain, the second best-placed candidate, shows an embarrassing lack of knowledge of the files.
Recently, he called for countering the Chinese military threat because Beijing is “trying to develop nuclear capability” – seemingly ignorant of the fact that China has held the military atom since 1964!
Texas Governor Rick Perry, who backs Israel and wants strikes against Iran, says he is ready to engage the U.S. military in Mexico against the drug cartels.
The use of torture against alleged terrorists, banned by Obama in 2009, is also advocated by Cain, Perry and candidate Michele Bachmann.
We are far from the 2008 Republican nominee, John McCain, a heavyweight in foreign policy.
The opponents of the current president reply that Reagan also had simple ideas and that he won the Cold War.
They recall that Obama himself was an amateur and that he had to put water in his wine when it came to counterterrorism.
They rightly insist on the failure of his naive dialogue with Iran, on the too hasty departure of the "boys" from Iraq, on his misrepresentations in Libya, thus sticking a label of weak.
But the attack is not so easy.
Obama’s national security assessment, which eliminated bin Laden, is seen as positive by the public.
Since Iraq, it has been wary of military interventions that lead to stalemate.
And, arguing that America needs to be rebuilt economically to resurrect its leadership, Obama strikes more justly.
The Nord Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe to Russia via the bottom of the Baltic Sea, has entered service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with brilliance.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, took part last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between orchestra and fine buffet, at the inauguration of the Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that directly connects, under the sea, Russia to Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte have turned the wheel of the valve together commanding the entry of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new pipeline, an additional 27.5 billion cubic meters of Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe through a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second tube is due to be completed at the end of 2012, providing a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we are already talking about the possibility of building a third one on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge construction site looks like victory.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic States.
Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any overland passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
As a result, these two countries lose some of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to close off its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw had not hesitated to compare the Nord Stream to a "new German-Soviet pact", in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the subject is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of the energy Europe, since the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has triumphed over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich, gas-consuming Western countries whose deposits are in decline.
"This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that links us organically," confirmed Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon when he inaugurated this pipeline, demonstrating how big gas contracts are as political as they are economic.
All this explains the broad smiles displayed by the leaders of Gazprom, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The underwater tube is made of steel lined with concrete to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from the Second World War.
“A hundred had to be kidnapped or destroyed, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
There was also a need for more measures to protect the flora and fauna.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts along its entire length: neither valve, nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but project officials gave it up while the Swedes were unwilling to see a Russian state-owned company permanently set up off their coasts.
“In case of damage, we stop the gas flowing in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In the event of leakage, the gas contained in the pipeline thus escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the manufacturers who have planned the welds for a leak every 100,000 years.
The state of the pipeline is monitored by an underwater robot, dragged by a ship, for external observation, as well as by an apparatus that circulates inside the pipeline.
From the shape of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, one meter wide, and it is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of 3 meters second, it provides accurate information on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The circulation of the gas is simply ensured by the pressure.
It is 200 bars on departure, and 100 on arrival.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
It was joined by German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch company Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the company’s entire gas transmission capacity for a renewable period of 20 years.
“Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” Müller said.
The financing of the construction of the pipeline was ensured at 30% by the shareholders and at 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the works is expected to reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment amounted to 240 million.
But the minority shareholders are sure to go back to their expenses, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas exit door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the incoming gas before it is transferred to German pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour that passes.
At full capacity, that will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created about fifteen years ago by an Italian company, the Moleskine wants to restore the taste of writing.
It has a scent of adventure, of hours spent writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognizable, with its black rectangular cover, its elastic, its leaves of a broken white color, as aged by time.
Yet the Moleskine notebook as we know it today was born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at the time to launch a notebook of design notes but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then a consultant for the company, is in charge of the launch of the new product.
The notebook is inspired by an ancient production technique, the mole skin, which designates a varnished cotton used to cover benches for example.
This type of notebook was very popular with writers and travelers.
“Moleskine brought to life an old and forgotten object, which was an icon of avant-garde artists, until the 20th century,” says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become the brand manager at Modo Modo.
The success is there.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26% to 12.7 million pieces sold.
We are far from the confidential production of the early years, when only 3,000 notebooks were designed.
Moleskine crosses Italian borders and exports to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
Difficult to establish a portrait-robot of the buyer, because the notebook appeals to both the businessman and the student and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its consumers are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cultured.
The small Italian company, which had 12 employees in its beginnings, now has almost 100 employees and since 2008 has two offices; one in Milan and the other in New York.
She distributes her notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to small shops in the city center and has managed to impose her identity.
“We have followed the times and this new need for writing, despite the rise of emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature accompanies the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand launched a "Detour" exhibition where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, she also launched a leopard cover at the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, diary, pens, computer covers... The brand is available on a whole range of supports.
A success that made envious: in the fall of 2006, Modo Modo was bought by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, today Syntegra Capital, writing a new page in the history of Moleskine.
Why is the unemployment rate for disabled workers still so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The 15th Week for Disabled Employment opens today.
Despite a proactive public policy implemented in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice the average: 19%, compared to 9% for the whole population.
Disheartening?
“No,” says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, director general of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of disabled people.
“The progress made in the last fifteen years is considerable.”
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher."
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It must be said that for the unemployed with disabilities, there are still many obstacles before accessing employment.
They are rather old: 37% are over 50 years old (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the baccalaureate and of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared to an average of 38%.
In short, all these criteria that make it very difficult to return to work, and which "constitute the core of the problem", according to Christian Grapin, general manager of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies recruit workers with disabilities.
This is for objective brakes.
The unspoken remains, the mentalities that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre pour la Cité indicated that the managers interviewed have "a low level of knowledge of disability", with an "overrepresentation of people in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled ".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees are still far from achieving the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, set in a law of 1987.
The last known figures, which date from 2008, show a ratio of 2.6%.
"We are now around 3%," says Pierre Blanc, general manager of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence is that the number of "taxed" institutions, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59 000 to 46 000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which increased contributions, created strong pressure on companies,” explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of establishments with 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared to 82% of enterprises with 100 to 199 employees.
